			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				Couple more thoughts: <br>  <br> 1) The key thing for players is they need to feel a small accomplishment had been made.  So the hilt of a sword can even have different materials such as wooden, silver, gold, platinum; and a player can collect all wooden pieces of a sword, or need to keep the wooden one in order to trade in for the silver.  This way a sense of progress can be felt through many small steps.  I'd love to be there when someone says he's just got the refined wooden hilt (wooden hilt #9) so he's closer to corse silver now.  I think EQ2 has already stated they will have quests that make players feel a bit of accomplishment at a time, so pardon me for repeating the idea. <br>  <br> 2) Also, EQ itself has many quests like this in the past in the traditional areas, except it usually involved one party to go to a specific spot to camp for something for someone, then go to another spot to camp for someone else.  I ran into this with my druid when he wanted a better shield.  My druid wanted to camp for something like 9 skulls in Luclin, but my warrior friend wanted to camp for the Iksar ceremonial bp which was in a different spot.  We were really close friends, yet we never did get to camp either spot because we didn't have that much time to play, and taking time to camp for mine, then for his items meant our leveling was going to take a hit.  And we'd be bored spending weeks at the same camp with only one of us having prospects of gaining a new item. <br>  <br> Lost Dungeon is fun because it allows every class in the group to work together and get what they need.  I'd like to see the skulls drop, and the components for a bp my warrior friend can use drop--both in the same dungeon.  So we can both have fun without feeling like one of us is sacrificing time for a whole week.
