		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				I don't get it. <br>  <br> Noone here gives one example of what they would like to see changed other then &quot;revamp zones.&quot; How? what content would you add? What do you think would draw players to the old un-used zones that are abandoned currently? If you like 95% of the players in EQ spend the majority of your time playing a level 50+ character why would you care if EQ revamps all those level 15-45 zones? It would be just like with all the other zones that were revamped, it is crowded with people above the level of the zone who farm it for loot for a week then is abandoned once more. <br>  <br> All this hand-wringing about the EVIL of Sony being a corporation and trying to earn the best profit they can is meaningless. They are all here to make money, in fact those MMORPGS that are not spewing out worthwhile expansions at a rate of at least 1 a year are dying. As was said above if you dislike the product do not buy it, if you no longer enjoy EQ then take a break or stop playing entirely. I don't listen to whiners in real life and I definately don't want to read it here, if you have suggestions about how to make EQ &quot;fun again&quot; please do share them as I would read those with interest. <br>  <br> The majority here writes that EQ has been devoting far too much time and content devoted towards the high end raiding &quot;uber-guild&quot; crowd and neglected the casual gamer. But the last 2 expansions were 90% devoted to what a casual group of 6 friends could do at their own pace? There are only 2 coherent complaints I've read above. The first, that is just plain silly, is how much longer it takes that casual group of friends to accomplish what a 60 person guild can do in one extended raiding session. But where is the logic in 6 people being able to accomplish the exact same results of what it took a raid force in less time? That just reads like pure ugly jealousy. The 2nd I will agree with, that LDON and GoD lacked a coherent lore, &quot;atmosphere&quot; and engaging story. Previous expansions to EQ felt like new lands or worlds being opened up to explore and adventure in with interesting races, their homes, their enemies, factions, dungeons and so on. LDON, GoD and to a somewhat lesser extent PoP were all about setting out specific goals for the players to challenge and overcome with specific rewards.  <br>  <br> Time is what makes all the difference in all these games ultimately, just like any other hobby. Those who can devote more to it get the most back in return, if what time you can spend in Norrath is no longer even entertaining merely for the sake of spending time with the friends you have made here, then I think you need a new hobby (like I am realizing for myself, nearly done with medical school and I about to kiss all my free time goodbye). <br>  <br> The main problem with GoD was how remote and difficult to reach most of it was, you basically had to struggle with a full group to reach the zone or goal you were after in the first place. This was especially troublesome in GoD trials as if someone was lost or disconnected it can mean having to refight your way back to the entrance with 100's of respawned mobs at your back to pick them back up and then turn around and do it all over again.  <br>  <br> In comparison to the ease of entry with even 1st through even 3rd tier PoP zones and LDON why bother with GoD- an expansion that was intended for casual players but required a minimum of an hour just to reach your starting point and worse still frequently required you to retrace and refight the areas you have been in multiple times to continue making progress? <br>  <br> 		

